<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-06-11T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-06-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="281" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d281">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">711.022/6–1153</note>
                    <head><hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Deputy Legal Adviser
                            (Tate)</hi></head>
                    <opener><dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1953-06-11">June 11,
                                1953</date>.</dateline></opener>
                    <list type="subject">
                        <item>Subject:</item>
                        <item>Continental Shelf Bill <gloss target="#t_S1">S.</gloss> 1901</item>
                    </list>
                    <p>Senator Cordon called me this afternoon and asked me if, from the
                        international viewpoint, it would be permissible to extend the Constitution
                        and laws of the United States to the seabed and subsoil of the continental
                        shelf if the bill made it clear that there was no attempt to extend the
                        applicability of United States law to the super-adjacent waters and air. I
                        told him that it would be permissible to do so.</p>
                    <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Jack B. Tate</hi></signed></closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>